Downtown Montreal Walk - April 12, 2025

Okay, so today's "power walk" through downtown Montreal was... well, let's just say I mostly powered through existential dread, fueled by stale croissants and the vague hope of spotting Ryan Reynolds. Spoiler alert: Ryan was a no-show, but the city still delivered some quirky goodness.

Starting near Place des Arts around 2:20 PM (give or take, my watch runs on "Montreal Time," which is apparently code for "whenever I feel like it"), I bravely ventured westward. The weather, bless its cotton socks, was gloriously indecisive. One minute sunshine, the next a drizzle that threatened to turn my hair into a tragic poodle situation. But hey, that's Montreal for ya!

My leisurely stroll took me past the Musée d'art contemporain de Montréal. Did you know that museum once hosted an exhibit dedicated entirely to poutine? Talk about a cultural experience!

I continued my westward trek, inching closer to the heart of downtown. My GPS indicates a brief detour closer to Dorchester Square. The square is named after Lord Dorchester, the Governor General of British North America back in the day, who was known for his rather eccentric habit of wearing a full suit of armor to formal dinners. Can you imagine?

Pushing on, I meandered towards the majestic St. Patrick's Basilica, its towering spires reaching for the heavens. Legend has it that during its construction in the mid-19th century, the Irish workers added a secret symbol on one of the stained-glass windows. To this day, no one has found it. Is it a shamrock, a map to hidden gold, or just a leprechaun playing tricks? The mystery continues!

Turning around and beginning to head Eastward, I was probably walking slightly faster, or maybe the earth was rotating faster than usual. A little further now I wandered near Phillips Square. Phillips Square is named for Thomas Phillips, Montreal's third mayor, who apparently had a real love of pigeons. During his mayorship, he introduced a city-wide pigeon feeding program. So if you see a lot of pigeons there, you know who to thank.

I continued to trudge along. A little later, I passed the Eaton Centre. During the Christmas season, the Centre installs mechanical scenes which are known as the "Twelfth Floor Windows" for their original location.

The walk concluded back where I began, Place des Arts, at approximately 4:20 PM. Two hours, a slightly soggy outfit, and zero Ryan Reynolds sightings. My pace could generously be described as "relaxed scenic appreciation," which is a fancy way of saying I stopped frequently to admire pigeons and question my life choices. I think I may have even done a loop. But hey, at least I got some fresh air and mildly amusing anecdotes!

Next adventure? I'm thinking a trek through Mount Royal Park. Supposedly, Frederick Law Olmsted, the designer of Central Park, also designed Mount Royal Park. Now if that isn't an impressive pedigree, I don't know what is.
